movement to tease out the diverging political strategies and contradictory tactics that distinguished the movement. By examining news articles and opinion pieces, as well as literary texts and photographs in the League’s numerous pulp magazines for homosexuals, Javier Samper Vendrell reconstructs forgotten aspects of the history of same-sex desire and subjectivity. While recognizing the possibilities of liberal rights for sexual freedom during the Weimar Republic, the League’s "respectability politics" failed in part because Radszuweit’s own publications contributed to the idea that homosexual men were considered a threat to youth, doing little to change the views of the many people who believed in homosexual seduction – a homophobic trope that endured well into the twentieth century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aGay liberation movementzGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aGaysxPolitical activityzGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aHomosexuality in literature. 0aHomosexualityzGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 0aSeductionzGermanyxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Germany.2bisacsh  aBerlin.  aBund für Menschenrecht.  aFriedrich Radszuweit.  aGermany.  aLeague for Human Rights.  aWeimar.  agay magazines.  ahistory of gay rights.  ahomosexual emancipation.  ahomosexuality.  aprint culture.  apulp magazines.  aqueer history.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069045340uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148753605340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487536053423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487536053.jpg  a978-3-11-069045-3  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles